This is a design that is quite obviously detrimental.

255
00:12:52,360 --> 00:12:53,820
So, the second question is...

256
00:12:53,820 --> 00:12:55,140
So, what about the current large models?

257
00:12:55,140 --> 00:12:58,560
So, how good is their memory really in long conversations?

258
00:12:58,560 --> 00:13:01,280
We've provided heatmaps for two matrices.

259
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:03,320
One is the overall score.

260
00:13:03,320 --> 00:13:07,110
and the other is the normalized memory score.

261
00:13:07,110 --> 00:13:11,930
If we just focus on the memory score, um, we'll find that...

262
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:15,640
And we made two key discoveries.

263
00:13:15,640 --> 00:13:19,120
The first point is that as the conversation gets longer,

264
00:13:19,120 --> 00:13:22,530
Now, the horizontal axis for both of these heatmaps...

265
00:13:22,530 --> 00:13:25,550
the different periods of the conversation,

266
00:13:25,550 --> 00:13:27,850
For example, from period zero to period ten.

267
00:13:27,850 --> 00:13:31,589
indicating different turns in the conversation, from light to dark, uh...

268
00:13:31,589 --> 00:13:32,489
As the conversation gets longer,

269
00:13:32,489 --> 00:13:36,430
we'll find that the model and the agent... uh...

270
00:13:36,430 --> 00:13:36,770
Sorry.

271
00:13:36,770 --> 00:13:39,830
And it's only when we test the models that we see their performance plummet.

272
00:13:39,830 --> 00:13:43,060
For most models, in the middle to later stages of the conversation,

273
00:13:43,060 --> 00:13:48,200
Its performance dropped to below 50% of its initial capability.

274
00:13:48,200 --> 00:13:50,220
Sometimes, it even drops below the random score.

275
00:13:51,300 --> 00:13:56,320
Second, the memory score is significantly lower than the 'abroad' score.

276
00:13:56,320 --> 00:13:59,260
In other words, as you can see in the chart, the score for the one on the right is lower than the one on the left.

277
00:13:59,260 --> 00:14:01,640
And this is also pretty intuitive.

278
00:14:01,640 --> 00:14:02,560
This is quite intuitive.

279
00:14:02,560 --> 00:14:07,480
Because that just reflects the model's surface-level fluency in its responses.

280
00:14:07,480 --> 00:14:11,530
This actually masks the failure of its underlying memory mechanism.

281
00:14:11,530 --> 00:14:13,250
So, the model might sound very confident,

282
00:14:13,250 --> 00:14:16,330
But in reality, it's already forgotten some key information.

283
00:14:17,510 --> 00:14:21,210
Alright, so the third question we're interested in is...

284
00:14:21,210 --> 00:14:24,190
So, can the external memory mechanism actually help?

285
00:14:24,190 --> 00:14:27,090
And by 'external memory', we mean something that exists outside of the model itself.

286
00:14:27,090 --> 00:14:29,410
We hooked up some external frameworks to assist the model.

287
00:14:29,410 --> 00:14:31,420
used to store memory information.

288
00:14:31,780 --> 00:14:33,320
We tested three different implementations.

289
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:36,900
Right, and you can see this implementation in the diagram on the right.

290
00:14:36,900 --> 00:14:39,340
The first is the traditional RAG.

291
00:14:39,340 --> 00:14:41,520
In other words, we store the entire conversation history.

292
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:43,910
into an external vector store.

293
00:14:43,910 --> 00:14:46,890
and retrieves the relevant information when answering questions.

294
00:14:46,890 --> 00:14:48,830
to use as context.

295
00:14:48,830 --> 00:14:51,249
And then there's also AWE.

296
00:14:51,249 --> 00:14:53,309
Agent-based External Memory.

297
00:14:53,309 --> 00:14:56,789
This means we let the agent decide for itself what information...

298
00:14:56,789 --> 00:14:58,000
what to store and what not to store.

299
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,840
and let it decide autonomously what gets stored in an external memory bank. Okay,

300
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:03,520
And there's another type, which is AWI.

301
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:06,790
That's right. It's the energetic memory in context.

302
00:15:06,790 --> 00:15:09,270
This part is somewhat similar to AWE.

303
00:15:09,270 --> 00:15:10,150
The difference is that...

304
00:15:10,150 --> 00:15:14,230
It just compresses the information into the large model's context.

305
00:15:14,230 --> 00:15:16,590
into the buffer, um...

306
00:15:18,910 --> 00:15:20,710
So, we've made a few discoveries here.

307
00:15:20,710 --> 00:15:25,470
First off, the AWE approach delivered the best performance.

308
00:15:25,470 --> 00:15:30,590
This means letting the model autonomously decide what information to filter and remember.

309
00:15:30,590 --> 00:15:34,230
This is more efficient than just storing everything.

310
00:15:34,840 --> 00:15:38,380
The second finding is that, uh, while RAG is very simple,

311
00:15:38,380 --> 00:15:40,860
not selective enough, hmm.

312
00:15:41,260 --> 00:15:44,100
Uh, but... but it's not selective enough.

313
00:15:44,100 --> 00:15:46,580
So that's what leads to this, uh...

314
00:15:46,580 --> 00:15:49,400
the results of retrieval are quite noisy.

315
00:15:49,400 --> 00:15:54,120
And this would lead to, uh, a... a... compared to AWE,

316
00:15:54,120 --> 00:15:56,710
a lower score, uh...

317
00:15:56,710 --> 00:15:58,130
What was surprising, though, was that...

318
00:15:58,130 --> 00:16:01,790
We found that the implementation of this memory mechanism, AWI...

319
00:16:01,790 --> 00:16:05,249
In other words, the model takes this memory content

320
00:16:05,249 --> 00:16:08,820
writes it into its own context.

321
00:16:08,820 --> 00:16:11,020
And in our tests, this strategy...

322
00:16:11,020 --> 00:16:13,460
It might even perform worse than the native one,

323
00:16:13,460 --> 00:16:17,440
The performance of large models actually gets worse with long contexts.

324
00:16:17,440 --> 00:16:20,260
This could mean compressing information into a buffer,

325
00:16:20,260 --> 00:16:24,400
it might actually lose some key details,

326
00:16:24,400 --> 00:16:27,780
It might even be more harmful than not compressing the information at all.

327
00:16:29,260 --> 00:16:34,570
And finally, we looked into the reasons why the models failed.

328
00:16:34,570 --> 00:16:37,079
and conducted a series of diagnostic analyses.

329
00:16:37,859 --> 00:16:39,319
Let's break it down into a few dimensions.

330
00:16:39,319 --> 00:16:41,919
First, let's look at the strategy dimension.

331
00:16:41,919 --> 00:16:44,840
As we just saw, there's also AGENTIC RISE.

332
00:16:44,840 --> 00:16:46,640
Its overall score is pretty good.

333
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:48,520
Through a more detailed diagnostic analysis,

334
00:16:48,520 --> 00:16:52,250
We found that it actually did improve...

335
00:16:52,250 --> 00:16:57,220
its ability to actually utilize the information it has stored.

336
00:16:57,220 --> 00:17:00,400
But the trade-off is that it sacrifices some of its read performance.

337
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:03,690
This could be because, uh, in the compressed information...

338
00:17:03,690 --> 00:17:07,710
during the process of compressing information into this external knowledge base.

339
00:17:07,710 --> 00:17:10,650
This compression process results in information loss.

340
00:17:11,010 --> 00:17:13,630
The second dimension is the update frequency.

341
00:17:13,630 --> 00:17:15,920
And here, we found that...

342
00:17:15,920 --> 00:17:19,060
The lower the frequency at which the agent writes to its memory,

343
00:17:19,060 --> 00:17:20,680
The lower this update frequency is,

344
00:17:20,680 --> 00:17:23,430
the higher its read failure rate becomes.

345
00:17:23,430 --> 00:17:26,310
This could be because it's retaining too many local messages.

346
00:17:26,310 --> 00:17:28,830
This can cause some confusion.

347
00:17:29,160 --> 00:17:32,640
Uh, also, there are some other factors like noise and top-k.

348
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:35,190
I won't go into too much detail on that.

349
00:17:35,190 --> 00:17:38,890
So, these diagnostic metrics allow us to do a few things.

350
00:17:38,890 --> 00:17:40,850
and make targeted optimizations.

351
00:17:40,850 --> 00:17:43,870
for the memory design of our agent.

352
00:17:43,870 --> 00:17:45,750
rather than just blindly trial-and-erroring.

353
00:17:45,750 --> 00:17:47,410
or making blind improvements.

354
00:17:50,539 --> 00:17:53,359
Ah, this chart here is also a table.

355
00:17:53,359 --> 00:17:57,979
So, this is about those diagnostic metrics we just mentioned.

356
00:17:57,979 --> 00:17:59,259
Explanation.

357
00:18:00,310 --> 00:18:05,490
Uh, and we also found that, uh, if we look at it from an overall metric...

358
00:18:05,490 --> 00:18:07,410
we found that, uh,

359
00:18:07,410 --> 00:18:10,710
Both RAG and AWE saw a significant reduction.

360
00:18:10,710 --> 00:18:13,150
Specifically, the utilization failure...

361
00:18:13,150 --> 00:18:15,750
In other words, the failure rate of utilization.

362
00:18:15,750 --> 00:18:20,360
dropping from 24% to around 7%.

363
00:18:20,360 --> 00:18:26,380
But at the same time, the errors for both write and read operations increased.

364
00:18:26,820 --> 00:18:28,800
In contrast, for a strategy like AWI,

365
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:31,020
its write failure rate,

366
00:18:31,020 --> 00:18:33,660
the write failure remains relatively low.

367
00:18:33,660 --> 00:18:36,330
But its read failure rate is extremely high.

368
00:18:36,330 --> 00:18:40,390
This might be because it's trying to compress its own information into... uh...

369
00:18:40,390 --> 00:18:42,390
in the process of managing its own context,

370
00:18:42,390 --> 00:18:44,449
and a lot of important information is lost.

371
00:18:44,729 --> 00:18:45,049
Uh...

372
00:18:45,049 --> 00:18:47,469
What we've found so far is that there isn't a single method,

373
00:18:47,469 --> 00:18:50,970
that can perform well in these three...

374
00:18:50,970 --> 00:18:54,310
perform well across the three types of failure rates.

375
00:18:54,310 --> 00:18:57,370
This trade-off might be one of the fundamental challenges in memory system design.

376
00:18:57,370 --> 00:18:59,290
a rather fundamental challenge.

377
00:19:00,520 --> 00:19:02,600
Alright, let's wrap things up.

378
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:03,500
Take a look.

379
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:08,740
First of all, on-policy evaluation reveals issues with off-policy...

380
00:19:08,740 --> 00:19:12,140
certain memory-related issues that benchmarks tend to掩盖.

381
00:19:12,140 --> 00:19:14,840
If you continue to evaluate memory using static data,

382
00:19:14,840 --> 00:19:17,300
you're very likely to get some misleading results.

383
00:19:17,300 --> 00:19:19,840
This is especially true for the evaluation of agents.

384
00:19:20,670 --> 00:19:23,910
The second point is that all current models...

385
00:19:23,910 --> 00:19:25,390
Even the most powerful ones,

386
00:19:25,390 --> 00:19:27,490
in long-context conversations,

387
00:19:27,490 --> 00:19:31,340
all have a significant limitation when it comes to memory.

388
00:19:31,340 --> 00:19:32,840
It's just superficial fluency.

389
00:19:32,840 --> 00:19:36,720
This might all be masking their actual memory failures.

390
00:19:37,850 --> 00:19:42,170
Third, external memory is helpful.

391
00:19:42,170 --> 00:19:45,020
But it's not perfect, um.

392
00:19:45,020 --> 00:19:49,460
And we found that among the several types we just mentioned...

393
00:19:49,460 --> 00:19:50,000
failure.

394
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:51,620
Writing, reading, and utilization.

395
00:19:51,620 --> 00:19:55,190
And there's a fundamental trade-off among these three types of failures.

396
00:19:55,190 --> 00:19:57,030
But right now, there isn't a single one.

397
00:19:57,030 --> 00:19:59,950
method that can effectively solve this problem.

398
00:20:00,510 --> 00:20:01,990
And for the fourth point...

399
00:20:01,990 --> 00:20:05,150
So, self-evolution might be a pretty promising direction.

400
00:20:05,150 --> 00:20:07,190
For the agent, we also conducted a pilot study.

401
00:20:07,190 --> 00:20:10,820
We found that AASIENT can leverage the feedback from MMGM.

402
00:20:10,820 --> 00:20:13,620
to iteratively optimize its own memory strategies.

403
00:20:13,620 --> 00:20:18,130
Right, this is something that might come up in its future self-evolution.

404
00:20:18,130 --> 00:20:22,309
Yeah, that's a pretty interesting insight, I'd say.

405
00:20:22,309 --> 00:20:25,269
So, it might use some other mechanisms to iterate on that.

406
00:20:25,269 --> 00:20:27,009
to optimize the memory strategies of Agent A itself.

407
00:20:27,009 --> 00:20:29,790
This could be a potential topic for future work.

408
00:20:30,810 --> 00:20:32,110
So, to sum it up,

409
00:20:32,110 --> 00:20:35,930
MMGM is a framework that evaluates the conditional agent memory,

410
00:20:35,930 --> 00:20:38,730
a reliable benchmarking diagnostic tool,

411
00:20:38,730 --> 00:20:42,890
and it also provides potential directions for optimization.

412
00:20:43,330 --> 00:20:46,980
Uh, alright, thank you all for your participation.

